International Tributes to the History of Flight
First Flight Over the North Pole
On May 11, 1926, the airship Norge, designed and
built by Umberto Nobile of Italy, stood ready at Spitz-
bergen, Norway. If all went well, it would carry Nor-
wegian explorer Roald Amundsen and American
financier Lincoln Ellsworth on an historic journey
over the North Pole.
Thirteen hours after lift-off — at 1:00 a.m. on May
12 — the airship soared over the North Pole. It then
continued on to Teller, Alaska.
The flight had unexpectedly become something of
a race. Two days earlier, Americans Richard Byrd and
Floyd Bennett set out for the Pole in the "Josephine
Ford." Despite Byrd's assertion that he reached the
Pole first, aviation experts contest the claim.
The full-color cachet shows the two crafts involved
in the race to the Pole. On the ground is Richard
Byrd's Fokker trimotor,
"Josephine Ford." Aloft is
Amundsen and Ellsworth's airship, the Norge.
Mint Stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover was issued
by Grenada in 1983 to commemorate the bicentennial
of manned balloon flight. It pictures the Norge dur-
ing its flight from Spitzbergen, Norway to Teller, Alaska
via the North Pole.
Postmark: This Cover was postmarked in Spitzber-
gen, Norway on May 12, 1984, the anniversary of the
first flight over the North Pole.
© Postal Commemorative Society
Pined 570. 027
